[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Hey guys, recently Ideogram released their open weight image generation model, Ideogram 4. Unlike other image generation models we have seen before, this model requires you to feed it a JSON prompt. It also uses B box values to determine the placement of objects in'

[00:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the output image, which is a fantastic feature. In this video, I will show you my three-step workflow for taming this 9.3 B model. This tutorial assumes that you already know where to download Ideogram and its related models, where'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to place them in ComfyUI, and that you have a basic understanding of how to use this model. So, let\'s get started. I have linked the three-step workflow I built for Ideogram 4 in the description below, so feel free to download it. Now,'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'let\'s jump in and start understanding how to use this workflow. So, the first step is converting our normal prompts into a JSON prompt. For that, we have this group called initial JSON prompt builder. In the initial prompt subgraph'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'node, we can type the standard prompts we use for other image generation models. Let\'s change the current prompt. I have a lot of prompts written in my notepad, so let\'s copy one of them. Let\'s use this one of a woman sleeping'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on a bed and paste it inside the initial prompt field. If the prompts are short, we can enhance them. To enhance the prompt, turn the enhance prompt switch to true. For prompt enhancement, I will be using the Gemma 4 E4BFP8 model,'

[01:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'though you can also use Qwen 3.5 4B. Then, we have the temperature, which sets the creativity of the model. I will set it to 0.6. If you want to increase the creativity,'

[01:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'increase the temperature, but keep in mind that there is a chance of deviation from the prompt we provided for enhancement. Therefore, I suggest using a lower temperature. Then, let\'s change the seed value. Now, let\'s enhance the'

[01:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'prompt. Select this enhanced prompt node and click on the small play button. So, here is our enhanced prompt. Now, it\'s time to turn this into a JSON prompt. For that, we use the JSON prompt builder'

[01:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'node. Select the node and run it. You will see a block of text combined with our enhanced prompt. Copy this text using the copy button. We now need to feed this into a larger parameter model capable of generating'

[02:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'high-quality JSON. If your computer can handle high parameter models locally, feel free to use them, or you can use Gemini, ChatGPT, Claude, or Grok instead. In my case, I am going to use'

[02:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Gemini. Let\'s switch over, paste the text, and press enter. After a few seconds, we get our JSON prompt. With the first step finished, let\'s move into the second step, refining this JSON'

[02:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'prompt. Copy the output, head back to ComfyUI, and go to the second group called refine JSON prompt. Let\'s paste the JSON prompt we just copied into the input your JSON prompt node. Now, we can'

[02:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'refine the JSON prompt using the Ideogram Four Prompt Builder KJ node from the ComfyUI KJ Nodes custom node pack. Let\'s load the JSON prompt into the node by selecting the preview as text node'

[02:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and clicking the small play button. And here we go. The JSON prompt is now loaded into the Ideogram Four Prompt Builder KJ node. If you don\'t want to use the Ideogram Four Prompt Builder KJ'

[03:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'node, you can set this switch to false. Now, let\'s get a basic understanding of this node. First, we have the image input for loading a reference image, which is useful for adjusting the'

[03:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'placement of objects and texts. Next, we have the import JSON input for loading existing JSON prompts, which is what we used for loading JSON prompt into the node. Then, we have the B boxes option. Remember, a lot of features are'

[03:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'frequently added to this node by the developer. This was a recent addition I haven\'t used much, so I\'m going to skip it. Be aware that this node changes often, so it may look different in the future than it does in this video. Now, regarding width and height, these set'

[03:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the canvas size of the editor shown at the bottom of the node. These dimensions should match the output resolution of the image you\'re trying to generate. Otherwise, the placement of objects might not match your expectations. In my case, I am using a square resolution of'

[04:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '1024. Next, we have the high-level description text box. This is where we write an overall description of the output image. Then, we have the background text box where we describe the scene behind our subjects or'

[04:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'objects. Next is the style drop-down menu for choosing between photo and art style. For realistic images, use photo. For other mediums, use art style. Since I\'m aiming for realism, I will select photo. When you select photo, you get a'

[04:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'photo text box to input keywords related to camera, shot type, or lens details. Then, we have the aesthetics text box. Put keywords here related to the look of your image. Is it cinematic, moody, or'

[04:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'desaturated? From my experience, don\'t use sentences. Using keywords separated by commas works much better. Next is lighting, where we describe the light and shadow details. Then, we have the'

[04:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'medium text box here. Define the medium that your output image falls under. For a photograph, type photograph. If you are generating graphic design-related images, type graphic_design. Note the underscore between graphic and'

[05:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'design. For an oil painting, type painting. Or, you can experiment with other mediums like comic or 3D render, depending on your needs. In my case, I\'m going to use photograph. Then, we have'

[05:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the style palette data, which decides the overall color combinations for the output. Here, you input the hex codes for the colors. You don\'t need to type these manually. Instead, use the style colors option.'

[05:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Right now, there are three colors added. So, using the plus sign, we can add more colors. For right now, I\'m going to stick with these three. Then, we have the elements data text box, where we'

[05:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'type the details of the objects or text we want to appear in our output image. To make it easier to add or edit this data, we have this editor at the bottom. Right now, there are two objects added, which appear as rectangles containing'

[05:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'their descriptions. They are currently in the wrong position, so we can adjust the scale and placement of both rectangles. In my case, a woman is sleeping on a bed, so we\'ll place the bed in the bottom right corner and the'

[06:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'woman on top of it. When we resize these rectangles, the Ideogram for prompt builder node automatically updates the bbox values of the corresponding objects in our JSON prompt. So, adjust the rectangle size and position according to'

[06:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your needs. The editor also makes it easy to edit individual object descriptions. Just select the rectangle you want to edit, and under the type object text menu, you will see a text box for modifications.'

[06:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Alternatively, you can double-click a rectangle to edit its description directly. To add more objects, just use your left mouse button to draw a new rectangle. Then, type in the description of what you want to appear. To remove an'

[06:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'object you don\'t need, right-click in an empty area, and click the cross button corresponding to that object. You can also duplicate existing objects. For text, draw a rectangle and select text in the type area. You can then describe'

[06:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the text you want and add style details. For example, specify if it should be bold, italicized, or use a particular font style. You can also convert existing objects into text elements, or set unique colors for each object using'

[07:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the colors option at the bottom. For now, I don\'t need separate colors, so I\'ll remove them. Now that our changes are made, to see the JSON prompt changes before sending it to the Ideogram model, run the preview as text node. Then, if'

[07:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we scroll down, we can see that the new bbox values have been added to our JSON prompt. That finishes step two. Let\'s move to the last step, generating the image. In this group, we won\'t look at every node, just the essentials. Here,'

[07:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we have the resolution and mode subgraph node where we can configure our output resolution and mode of generation. Under the resolution drop-down menu, you will find several recommended resolution'

[07:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'presets. If you need a specific size, choose custom resolution and manually enter your desired width and height. For now, I will stick to a square resolution. Next, the mode option. The default is 20 steps for standard'

[08:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'quality. There is also a turbo mode for faster generation, which is actually quite decent. Also, there is a quality 40 steps for even better quality, which can be quite slow. So, I\'ll stick to the default 20 steps. For the main CFG,'

[08:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'ll use 7.0 to ensure strong prompt adherence. However, using 7.0 for the entire generation can sometimes lead to quality issues. To fix this, we have a CFG'

[08:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'override that decides when to switch to a lower CFG value, in my case, 3.0. When generation hits about 90%, it switches to 3.0. If you still notice quality issues, try reducing the start'

[08:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'percentage to 0.6. Increasing the steps can also improve your output quality. That\'s it. Now, let\'s hit the generate button and see the result. So, here we go. The'

[08:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generation is finished. Let\'s take a look. As you can see, we got a nice result. There are some minor issues, especially with the windows and the blanket, though the blanket issue can probably be ignored. Overall, it\'s a'

